[SourceTitle "01 Introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/317883"]

{Over the years we have gradually come to understand the true nature of chess. 
Correspondence chess - a sublime search for truth. OTB - a tense and noble 
struggle. Blitz - one of mankind's earliest attempts to invent the video game. 
But it is no worse for that. In between working on my endgame book, I have 
another project: Making a detailed repertoire based on sound lines which happen 
to score best on Lichess for players in the 2000 - 2200 rating range. It is 
already quite a large work - 50 plus lines, some of which are 30 or more moves 
deep. This book is different. The same idea - lines which score very well in 
practice - but aimed at players 1600 and below. There are fewer lines to learn, 
and in a much more manageable depth. Analytical soundness is very much less to 
the fore - indeed, some of them are almost dubious. And yet I have faith that 
these lines would score far better in practice than they really ought to. The 
core of the repertoire is a set of interpretations of the Blackmar-Diemer gambit 
- but more often than not castling queen, rather than kingside. Black has the 
chance to sidestep into other lines - but I have found thematically similar 
attacks against most of those as well. I can't promise you'd win a 
correspondence chess championship with these lines- but I can promise an easy to 
learn set of lines with very good practical hacking chances. As an appetiser, 
here is a game I played against a weak computer immediately after finishing the 
book. Not a great work of art, but going from 'main line' to 'mated' over the 
course of three moves gives a taste of what is to come. I wish you all the 
best:)} 1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bf5 7. g4 
Bd7 8. Ne5 Bc6 9. Bc4 Bxh1 10. Bxf7# *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Teichmann defense with Bxf3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/317754"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 {The Teichmann defence, 
very popular and probably the one you will face most often. Now Black can either 
take on f3 or retreat the bishop - in which case only h5 really makes sense.} 6. 
h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 {Black has to defend b7, and Nc6 would get hit by Bb5} 8. Be3 
e6 9. O-O-O {White can either castle queenside, or prepare castling kingside 
with Bd3. Both are reasonable, but OOO followed by g4 is a nice easy plan.} Nbd7 
10. g4 {Black has problems to solve whichever way he sends his king. If Be7 then 
g5 begins an attack on his king. If Qa5, preparing ...OOO, then B - c4 - b3 (to 
protect the a2 pawn if the c3 knight needs to move) and White threatens g5 
followed by Qxf7} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Teichmann defense with Bh5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/317796"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 {The Teichmann defence, 
very popular and probably the one you will face most often.} 6. h3 Bh5 {The 
trouble with this move is that even on g6 the bishop finds itself a target, and 
it naturally provokes an attack on the kingside.} 7. g4 {As so often the case in 
openings where Black plays an early Bg4, h3 Bh5 is met by g4 Bg6 Ne5 and then 
Bg2.} Bg6 8. Ne5 e6 9. Bg2 c6 10. h4 {White has various moves here, but the 
simple charge looks good - and also arises from our line against 5...Bf5} Bb4 
{Black's only good move.} 11. Bg5 {White's king would actually stand pretty well 
on the kingside. But we will develop a piece and see if our opponent lets us 
sneak in OOO} Qa5 {Black needs to go long himself. Qa5 is a better way of 
preparing this than the immediate Nbd7, which runs into 12 h5, and White is 
better.} 12. Bd2 {Now our d pawn is safe, but the knight attacked twice, we pull 
the bishop back. 12... Nbd7 now runs into 13 Nxd7 followed by h5, so Black 
probably needs to play Qb6 .} Qb6 13. Qe2 {Preparing OOO. If Black now plays 
Qxd4, then after 14 OOO White is actually winning!} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The Blackmar Diemer"]
