1. d4 Nf6 {With this move order, Black has an annoying defence against our 
line.} 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 Nxe4 4. Nxe4 dxe4 5. Bc4 Bf5 6. g4 Bg6 7. Ne2 e6 8. h4 
{As every modern chess player knows, H is for Harry!} h6 9. Nf4 Bh7 10. g5 Qd6 
{Threatening Qb4+} 11. c3 e3 {Threatening Qc6 forking c4 and h1} 12. Qf3 Qc6 13. 
Qxc6+ Nxc6 14. g6 exf2+ 15. Kxf2 Bxg6 16. Nxg6 fxg6 17. Bxe6 {If Black has 
played well enough to reach here he has survived to an equal, but imbalanced 
ending. White has the bishops and the better pawn structure and development. On 
the other hand White's king can still cause problems and the Black kingside 
pawns are something of a concern.} *

