1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 e5 {Ok, it's actually called the Lemberger. 
Objectively, I have to admit it is fairly good. But you know what I'm talking 
about, South Park fans.} 4. Nxe4 exd4 5. Nf3 Bb4+ {Maybe not the absolutely best 
move, but you can count on seeing it quite a lot. If instead Nc6, then Bb5.} 6. 
c3 dxc3 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. O-O-O+ Bd7 11. Nxf6 gxf6 12. 
Bh4 {White has an easier position to play, and more or less compensation for the 
pawn. His light square bishop if probably going to c4 then b3, maybe knight to 
d4, Rhe1 etc.} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Teichmann defense with Bh5: White"]
[Black "compensation after 13 ...Bxc2?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/601588"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 {The Teichmann defence, 
very popular and probably the one you will face most often.} 6. h3 Bh5 {The 
trouble with this move is that even on g6 the bishop finds itself a target, and 
it naturally provokes an attack on the kingside.} 7. g4 {As so often the case in 
openings where Black plays an early Bg4, h3 Bh5 is met by g4 Bg6 Ne5 and then 
Bg2.} Bg6 8. Ne5 e6 9. Bg2 c6 10. h4 {White has various moves here, but the 
simple charge looks good - and also arises from our line against 5...Bf5} Bb4 
{Black's only good move.} 11. Bg5 {White's king would actually stand pretty well 
on the kingside. But we will develop a piece and see if our opponent lets us 
sneak in OOO} Qa5 {Black needs to go long himself. Qa5 is a better way of 
preparing this than the immediate Nbd7, which runs into 12 h5, and White is 
better.} 12. Bd2 {Now our d pawn is safe, but the knight attacked twice, we pull 
the bishop back. 12... Nbd7 now runs into 13 Nxd7 followed by h5, so Black 
probably needs to play Qb6 .} Qb6 13. Qe2 Bxc2 {One of two ways Black can grab 
further material here. Black can go on to get 4 pawns for the piece, and 
Tempranillo was asking about White's compensation. While it would be next to 
impossible (especially in a book like this one) to give all the possible 
resulting lines, it can be fun to play around with the position and see how 
White's activity makes problems for Black.} 14. Rc1 Bg6 15. h5 Bxh5 16. gxh5 
Qxd4 17. Rd1 Nbd7 18. Nxd7 Nxd7 {If Qxd7 White plays h6.} 19. Ne4 Ke7 {If Black 
plays 19...OO then 20 Bc3 Bxc3 21bc Qe5 22 Rxd7, and White wins another piece. 
If Black plays 19...OOO then 20 a3 Bxd2 21 Rxd2 Qe5 22 Nd6+ Kc7 23 Nxf7 and 
Black is crushed. If 19...Qxb2 then 20 OO! (with the threat of Rb1), Be7 21 Rb1! 
(anyway) Qxa2 22 Rxb7 Rb8 (nudging the White rook to c7 before defending the 
knight) 23 Rc7 Rd8 24 h6! Rg8 25 Qh5 g6 26 Qh2 (threatening Nd6+) Qa3 27 Rxc6 
and White's threats include Ng5, Bg5, Qc7 and Bc3 - Stockfish scores White at 
around +5 here.} 20. Bc3 Bxc3+ 21. bxc3 Qb6 22. Qd2 Rhd8 23. Qd6+ Ke8 24. Qg3 h6 
25. Qxg7 Qe3+ 26. Kf1 Qf4+ 27. Ke2 Qe5 28. Qxh6 {We will stop here as it is 
extremely unlikely one of your games will get this far. Stockfish calls this 
around +2 for White. The basic theme is that as long as White keeps posing 
threats, Black never quite gets his pieces into play and material gradually 
drops off. A human (especially a relative beginner) will attack worse than a 
computer. But they will defend WAY worse than a computer. Despite the White 
king's lack of pawn cover, he is so active thatit should actually be Black who 
is more accident prone.} *

