[White "Teichmann defense with Bh5: White"]
[Black "compensation after 13 ...Qxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/601589"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 {The Teichmann defence, 
very popular and probably the one you will face most often.} 6. h3 Bh5 {The 
trouble with this move is that even on g6 the bishop finds itself a target, and 
it naturally provokes an attack on the kingside.} 7. g4 {As so often the case in 
openings where Black plays an early Bg4, h3 Bh5 is met by g4 Bg6 Ne5 and then 
Bg2.} Bg6 8. Ne5 e6 9. Bg2 c6 10. h4 {White has various moves here, but the 
simple charge looks good - and also arises from our line against 5...Bf5} Bb4 
{Black's only good move.} 11. Bg5 {White's king would actually stand pretty well 
on the kingside. But we will develop a piece and see if our opponent lets us 
sneak in OOO} Qa5 {Black needs to go long himself. Qa5 is a better way of 
preparing this than the immediate Nbd7, which runs into 12 h5, and White is 
better.} 12. Bd2 {Now our d pawn is safe, but the knight attacked twice, we pull 
the bishop back. 12... Nbd7 now runs into 13 Nxd7 followed by h5, so Black 
probably needs to play Qb6 .} Qb6 13. Qe2 Qxd4 {This seems to be an even worse 
pawn grab than Bxc2. Black only gets three pawns for the piece, and there is a 
rather spectacular difference in the safety of the respective castled 
positions.} 14. O-O-O Nbd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. h5 Bxh5 17. gxh5 O-O-O {Qe7 is a 
slight improvement, but OOO looks thematic.} 18. Bf4 Nd5 {Otherwise White will 
probably play Qe5.} 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Qf2 Bd6 21. Bh3 f5 22. Bg5 Rdf8 23. Qxa7 
{Given that Stockfish now tries to defend by ...b5 (met by Qd4, Rhe1 and a4) we 
can safely stop here and claim White is winning.} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Zeller Defence"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The Blackmar Diemer"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/1947353"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Bf5 {As requested by hlpfhugo. Black can use this to 
transpose to the Vienna, but he may decide to have a little snack after all. In 
which case we should give him something to wash it down with from the (bad pun 
alert:) whine Zeller.} 4. f3 {So, 4 .... Nf6 is sensible here. Instead:} exf3 5. 
Qxf3 {5 Nxf3 is almost ok here, eg 5...e6 6 Bd3 Bxd3 7 Qxd3 (idea B to d2 or g5, 
O-O-O and g4). But Qxf3 is much more fun and objectively stronger.} Qc8 {We are 
hitting f5 and b7. Now 5...Bc8?! 6 Bc4 is good for White, and Black has various 
ways to give up the b pawn and be only slightly worse. But Qc8 is thematic and 
almost always played.} 6. Bc4 e6 7. g4 {7 Nge2, 7 Bf4, and 7 d5 are all 
alternatives here. But g4 is most fun and possibly best.} Bxc2 {Black has had 
his first course; he can decline pudding with 7...Bg6; we would continue 8 Nge2 
and 9 O-O, probably with g5 to follow.} 8. Qe2 Bg6 9. Nf3 Nf6 $6 {Very natural, 
but an error. Black should play Bd6 here. Then 10 d5 (or 10 h4 h5 11 d5) e5 11 
Nxe5 Kf8 12 Bd2 and White still has pressure, even after 12...Qe8! 13 Nxg6 hg 14 
OO.} 10. h4 {Seems to be even better than the immediate d5.} Nxg4 11. d5 h5 {Or 
Bh5 12 de6 etc.} 12. dxe6 f6 13. Nd5 Nc6 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 cxd6 16. Rc1 Qd8 
{Slightly better than 16 ...O-O ?! 17 e7 Rf7 18 Nf4 Bf5 19 OO ++/--} 17. Bb3 Rb8 
18. O-O Ne7 19. Qb5+ Kf8 20. Nd4 a6 {The Queen sacrifice Nxe7 ab Nxg6 is 
perfectly good here, but in keeping with the rest of the repertoire we shall 
eschew wild complications and aim for a safe positional edge. XD} 21. Qb4 {White 
is winning. The threat is Nxe7 Qxe7 Qb6, idea Rc7. Black should probably run 
with Kg8. But if he were strong enough to have found this defence, he wouldn't 
have chosen this defence.} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "Other lines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mainline Classical French"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Other lines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/2217644"]

1. d4 Nf6 {With this move order, Black has an annoying defence against our 
line.} 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 e6 {Curses! Via this move order we can be forced to play 
some kind of classical French. This raises a bit of a dilemma; the best moves 
here are clearly e5 or Bg5 but those moves involve learning a lot of extra 
theory - especially annoying if you already have a detailed anti French 
repertoire based on 3 Nd2 or 3 e5! Unfortunately, most cop outs aren't very good 
here; 4 Nge2, 4 Be3 and 4 f3 all fail to impress. 4 Bd3 and 4 Qd3 are actually 
reasonably interesting, though equal. But in the end, I have decided to opt for 
something with fairly easy play and clear plans. Statistically, White hasn't 
done very well after 3 ed - but then, they haven't usually followed up well, 
whereas French players get the exchange variation all the time, usually from 
weaker players who are trying to keep things simple. And although I don't 
believe 4 ed followed by 5 Bd3 is objectively as good as 4 e5 or 4 Bg5, it does 
seem to be a reasonable try for an advantage, as in our main line here.} 4. exd5 
exd5 5. Bd3 {The plan we follow here actually fits well with the rest of the 
repertoire here; quick queenside development, OOO and attack on the kingside.} 
Bd6 6. Bg5 c6 7. Qf3 {White players that reach this position have typically gone 
Nge2, which doesn't seem bad either.} Nbd7 {Black can hit us with Bg4 here, but 
then he will find Qe3+ annoying.} 8. O-O-O O-O {It is hard to see Black 
successfully arranging to castle queenside himself.} 9. Nge2 {h4 followed by 
something to g5 is also common but the engines suggest this is better.} b5 10. 
Ng3 b4 11. Na4 {This type of move looks funny at first, but 'knight to rook 4' 
is often the best response to a- and b- (or g- and h-) pawn attacks. It is quite 
hard to attack, and it is looking at c5; and if necessary it can be supported by 
b3 and then retreat to b2. The main point however is that it simply holds up 
Black's pawn storm.} Qa5 12. b3 Re8 {If they play Ne4, be careful to take with 
the bishop; Ne4 Nxe4?? de Qxe4 loses to Qg5.} 13. Rhe1 Ba6 {Nb6?? loses to Bxf6} 
14. Bxa6 {Or perhaps Nf5 right away} Qxa6 15. Nf5 {White is doing well here; for 
example ...Bf8 Nh6+, or ...Ne4 Nxd6 Nxd6 (Nxg5?? Qf5 ++/--) So in summary, a 
playable, reasonably simple line but with lots of tricky little tactics. 
Perfect!} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "Other lines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
