{The old Benoni. This is probably the most practical way to play against the 
Sniper (g6, Bg7, c5) too.} 1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e4 Bg7 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. 
Bb5+ Bd7 7. a4 {To stop Black from having too easy a time playing a6 followed by 
b5.} O-O 8. O-O Na6 9. Re1 Nc7 10. Bf1 a6 11. a5 {Left to his own devices, White 
has plenty of useful moves - for instance Bg5, Qd2, h3, perhaps N-d2-c4 and 
eventually e5. But Black will be thrashing around and the actual play will 
probably revolve around taking advantage of the weaknesses he creates as he does 
so. ...b5 will of course usually be met by ab6. On the other hand, Black may try 
to ease congestion by playing a minor piece to b5 or breaking with e6. In any 
case, in this line we have the luxury of being the ones with the sound position, 
while the opponent peddles slightly more dubious wares.} *

