1. d4 b6 {Rather than c4, with the English defence, we play e4 and transpose to 
the Owen's. There is a nice line against this: Nc3, Bd3, Nge2. When it works 
well it works really well. I have played the following game several times.} 2. 
e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 Bb4 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O O-O 8. Nxd5 Bxd5 9. Nf4 
Bb7 10. Nh5 Be7 11. Nxg7 Kxg7 12. Qh5 Rh8 13. Bh6+ Kg8 14. Qg4+ Bg5 15. Bxg5 
{And Black isn't so much toast as finely ground charcoal.} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "Other lines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Owen's defense. Too cute!!"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Other lines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/1565976"]

1. d4 b6 {Rather than c4, with the English defence, we play e4 and transpose to 
the Owen's. There is a nice line against this: Nc3, Bd3, Nge2. When it works 
well it works really well. I have played the following game several times.} 2. 
e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 Bb4 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O Nxc3 {This is actually 
more popular than the OO I gave in the first line. But the attacking ideas are 
very similar.} 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Nf4 Nc6 {Congratulations! A lost position (for our 
opponent) after 9 moves. After getting hacked up on the kingside a few times, 
Black players often decide to try to go queenside with Nc6, d6, Qd7. Turns out 
move order is important though...} 10. Nh5 g6 11. Ng7+ {Into the valley of 
death... thumbing his nose at the Black king!} Kf8 12. Bh6 Kg8 13. Nh5 
{Threatening Qg4 followed by f4 f5} gxh5 {Not a clever capture - the computer is 
saying '+4' now...} 14. Qxh5 {One almost suspects some sort of 
Lancelot/Guinevere background here. The queen is really keen to avenge the 
knight.} f5 15. Qxf5 {I mean, REALLY keen!} exf5 16. Bc4+ {The state funeral is 
something to see. Both bishops attend.} d5 17. exd6# {But they have to keep the 
crowd at a safe distance. Boom! Isn't that just the prettiest mating sequence?} 
*

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "Other lines"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Hippo Critical"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Other lines"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/1634699"]

{Hippos (characterized by Black developing his bishops at g7 and b7 while 
staying restrained in the centre) come in all shapes and sizes, and degrees of 
respectability. Playing White of course, we want to crush the damn swamp 
grovelers. They often arise via a modern (g6,d6) move order, in which case we 
may be already committed to an early Be3. In this case do not despair, both the 
plans f4, Nf3 Bd3 OO and Qd2, f3 and possibly OOO can work well. But if possible 
get at least one of your bishops pawns going. The d4/e4/f4 setup is my favourite 
and often leads to Black getting blown off the board. You can often adopt it 
against all sorts of hippos. Some quick guidelines: When Black plays an early 
Nf6, e5 is often very strong; when he plays an early c5 the best reply is often 
to take it. On the other hand, once you see g6, you are really hoping to get in 
f5.} 1. d4 b6 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 g6 5. f4 Bg7 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. O-O {Black 
really ought to castle now, after which a plan of f5, Bg5 and perhaps Q-e1-h4 
works well. Instead, Black players often try to be cagey with their king...} d6 
$2 8. f5 exf5 {Maybe not best, but by far the most frequently played} 9. exf5 
O-O {If instead Nxf5 then Bxf5 followed by Bg5.} 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bd2 {11 fg also 
wins, but this sets a little trap. Against most moves we will play fg followed 
by Ne2 next; but in low level blitz Black often tries to keep things blocked...} 
g5 12. h4 h6 {If 12...g4 we play Nh2 followed by N-e2-f4! and Black is toast - 
his weaknesses on h5 and e6 are glaring.} 13. hxg5 hxg5 14. Nxg5 {A very easy 
sacrifice to make, even given that the d pawn goes too.} fxg5 15. Bxg5 Bxd4+ 16. 
Kh1 Qd7 17. Qg4 {With threats of a) Qxd4, b) f6 and c) various bishop 
discoveries, Black is busted, and has very little chance of survival even in a 
typically random bullet game.} *

