1. d4 d5 2. e4 c5 {Not very common, but does come up sometimes, and had a 
question about it. Not surprisingly though, it really isn't very good.} 3. dxc5 
d4 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e5 6. Bb5 Bxc5 7. Nxe5 Ne7 {Most common, and an error. 
Better is 7...Qb6, after which 8 Bxc6 bc 9 O-O and White is winning anyway.} 8. 
Nxf7 Kxf7 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qxc5 *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Beating Scott in the French"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/319252"]

{To round things out I thought I'd give some sample games. Pure human v human 
blitz games would be fun (and if you have played a good one with these lines, 
send it in and I'll add it!) but for the purposes of this book I have 
'manufactured' some examples by finding optimal play against computer opposition 
of various strengths - typically 10 minute games against the computer opponents 
that come free with the ICC interface 'dasher'. In a sense, these lines are 
'informational' - but I have left the option to learn them open. Do so or not as 
you like, but either way I hope you enjoy them:)} 1. d4 d5 2. e4 e6 3. Be3 dxe4 
4. Nd2 Bb4 {'Scott' is the weakest opponent, and this is his first bad move. 
He's not losing yet, but White is comfortably better after c3.} 5. c3 Bd6 6. 
Nxe4 Be7 {Have a tempo! The bishop should have retreated here straight away.} 7. 
Nf3 Nd7 8. Bd3 Ngf6 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black can play these structures sometimes in 
the Caro Kann and the Scandinavian. But he gets a very bad version here. If he 
wasn't losing before he is now.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Bh6 Re8 12. Re1 Kh8 13. Nd2 {A 
nice move, perhaps routing round to e4 or c4, but most of all simply getting out 
of the way of the queen, and, as we will see soon, the rook.} f5 14. Qh5 Kg8 15. 
Re3 b6 16. Rg3+ Kh8 17. Bg7+ Kg8 18. Bf6+ Kf8 19. Qh6# *

