{Andrew is the next level up. Meant to be a little stronger than Scott. Let's 
see...} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 Nc6 {Not bad squares for the knights - but the 'Black 
knights tango' works better against 2 c4.} 3. d5 Nb4 {This guy needed to go to 
e5, when Black is merely a lot worse. Now he's actually losing. Providing we 
don't try to attack the knight with Qd4?? of course...} 4. e4 b6 5. e5 Ng8 
{Home, home on the range...} 6. Nf3 Nh6 {You have to admit, it's a good start.} 
7. e6 Rg8 {This is a funny old move. Lets be kind and call it prophylaxis 
against Bxh6.} 8. Bxh6 {Kinder still, we let Andrew demonstrate his idea. Look 
at that lovely rook on g8!} gxh6 9. Ne5 {ef7 mate would amuse.} fxe6 10. Qf3 {Of 
course, he has to play Rg7, after which Qh5+ is splat. Instead...} Bb7 11. Qf7# 
{Good thing he's mated, or he'd lose his rook...} *

