{The next two opponents lose in the same way as Scott and Andrew. Then we come 
to Peter the park player. How will he fare?} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 Nxe4 4. 
Nxe4 dxe4 5. Bc4 {Quite a good line of the Hubsch for Black, especially if he 
follows up with ...e5} Nc6 6. Be3 {...which he doesn't.} Na5 7. Bxf7+ {Don't you 
just hate it when that happens?} Kxf7 8. Qh5+ Kf6 9. Qxa5 Bf5 10. Qe5+ Kg6 11. 
g4 Bd7 {If he had taken on g4, Qg5+ wins the bishop.} 12. Qh5+ Kf6 13. g5+ Ke6 
14. g6 Ba4 15. Qg4+ Kd6 16. Bf4+ Kd5 17. c4+ Kxd4 18. Qe6 hxg6 19. Be3+ Kd3 20. 
Qe5 Kxc4 21. Qc5+ Kd3 22. Qc3# {If this game had a theme tune, it would be 'Come 
to Daddy' by Aphex Twin. In fact, it is even more fun if you play through it 
with the Twin blaring in the background.} *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Peter Park Player makes"]
[Black "it to the endgame!"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/319424"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 Nxe4 4. Nxe4 dxe4 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. Be3 Bf5 {A big 
improvement on Na5??} 7. d5 Ne5 8. Qd4 {Giving up the bishop pair but speeding 
up development.} Nxc4 9. Qxc4 e5 10. dxe6 Bxe6 {Giving back the e pawn or the b 
pawn.} 11. Qb5+ c6 12. Qxb7 Qc8 13. Qxc8+ Bxc8 {An endgame pitting bishop pair 
against development and structure. Probably about even and at least he won't 
fall for any silly mates... will he?} 14. O-O-O Be6 15. Ne2 Rd8 16. Rxd8+ Kxd8 
17. Rd1+ Kc7 18. Rd4 Bd6 19. Rxe4 Bd5 20. Ra4 Ra8 21. Nc3 Bxg2 22. Rg4 Bf3 23. 
Rxg7 Rf8 24. Rxh7 a5 25. Bh6 {Ouch. If the rook moves then Rxf7+ wins his bishop 
on f3.} Kd7 26. Bxf8 Bf4+ 27. Kb1 Ke6 28. Na4 f5 29. Nc5+ Kd5 30. Rd7+ Kc4 31. 
b3+ Kb4 32. a3+ Kxa3 33. Rd4 Bxh2 34. Ra4# *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Jennifer's Opposite"]
[Black "Castling Ordeal"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/562153"]

{'Jennifer' is rated around 1800 and can be quite tricky if you are careless. 
But her defence goes quickly wrong, staring with 6...Bd7? and soon collapses.} 
1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bd7 {This bishop 
should have retreated to h5 or taken on f3; despite being a pawn down, White is 
already a little better.} 7. Bc4 Nc6 8. Qe2 {To meet e6 with d5!} Na5 {Removing 
the knight from c6 and the bishop from c4 is necessary to make ...e6 playable 
without immediate disaster.} 9. Bd3 e6 10. Bd2 Bb4 {And ...c5 was a better try 
here. White is now probably winning!} 11. a3 Be7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. g4 Bc6 14. g5 
Nd7 {This guy should have gone to h5 to try to hold up the pawns a little.} 15. 
Ne4 b6 16. h4 Bd5 17. g6 hxg6 {The last hope here was ...f5. Now it's a 
massacre.} 18. h5 f5 19. hxg6 fxe4 20. Bxe4 {The standard Rh8+ Kxh8 Qh2+ isn't 
as good after Bh4! Nxh4?! (Ng5!) Kg8! Ng2 Rf2! and the king lives a little while 
longer.} Nc4 {Now it is mate in 6. For what it is worth Bxe4 was better with 
'only' a +10 advantage in 'computer speak'.} 21. Bxd5 {21 Rh8+ still isn't 
mating - though it is crushing after 21 ... Kxh8 22 Qh2+ Bh4 23 Bg5! Note that 
in this line, 23 Nxh4?? fails after 23 ... Kg8, and White only has a clear 
advantage (after 24 Bxd5). The computer calls that +1, despite White's missing 
rook.} Nce5 22. Nxe5 Rf6 23. Qh5 exd5 24. Qh8# *

[Event "A beginner's blitz repertoire"]
[Site "The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Destroying David's Defences"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 The lines in practice: Sample games."]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832, variation/3624825"]

{David is quite a tough opponent. He is meant to be around 2000 elo. But against 
the Blackmar, his defence is lamentable and his demise laughable.} 1. d4 d5 {In 
this game I have used the 'Veresov' move order. It allows the Hubsch (probably 
not a good idea), but hints that we may vary from our BDG with 3 Bg5, or 
Jobava's Bf4. I have stuck to 2 e4 in the rest of the repertoire. It is also 
worth noting that if you really hate the Hubsch, then after 1 d4 Nf6 you can 
play 2 f3 d5 3 e4 de 4 Nc3.} 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 dxe4 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 Bg4 6. h3 
Bd7 {If you recall, Scott plays Bf5? here. Bxf3 and Bh5 are better moves. After 
bd7, we have slightly more than full compensation for our pawn. Against Jennifer 
we played Bc4. Bd3 is also good. If it helps, remember 'd for David' :)} 7. Bd3 
Nc6 8. O-O Nb4 {He clearly wants our bishop.} 9. Bc4 {Since you are asking so 
nicely... No.} Bf5 {Oops!} 10. Bxf7+ {A little twist on a familiar tactic. We 
sacrifice our bishop for his f- pawn, and then win his bishop back. Because 
guarding it with his king would really be asking for it...} Kxf7 11. Ne5+ Ke6 
{'I'd like some 'it' please'. Es Craaaaayzzeeee.} 12. Rxf5 Kxf5 13. Ne2 {A very 
nice quiet move, while a rook down. We are going to take away d5 and e6, and if 
necessary mobilise our c pawn.} Qe8 {Black is toast, but Ke6 is a better 
fighting try. The trouble is that we control d7 and f7, so he can't finish 
escaping. After 13...Ke6 14 c4! The computer clls it +8 or so.} 14. Nf4 {Now g4 
is looking big} h5 {And this won't be enough to stop it.} 15. Qf3 Na6 {The 
knight clearly cant bear to watch. Maybe it's hoping to sneak onto the next 
board.} 16. g4+ Nxg4 17. hxg4+ hxg4 18. Qxg4+ Ke4 {As Kf6?! Nd5 mate.} 19. Ne2+ 
Kd5 20. Nc3+ Kd6 21. Nc4+ Kc6 22. Qe6# {Clearly a position for 'test your chess 
humour'. The fact that the White king has no pawn cover left somehow adds to the 
effect.} *

